<subSubSection pageId="33" pageNumber="34" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1436,1410,1579]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,1482,1507]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ros-Farre &amp; Pujade-Villar" authorityYear="2013" box="[328,528,1483,1507]" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Aspicera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kovalevi">
<emphasis box="[328,528,1483,1507]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Aspicera kovalevi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
belongs to the group of species having sharp punctuation on scutum and lacking median mesoscutal carina. The most important character that distinguishes 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ros-Farre &amp; Pujade-Villar" authorityYear="2013" box="[1010,1136,1518,1542]" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Aspicera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kovalevi">
<emphasis box="[1010,1136,1518,1542]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">A. kovalevi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the scutellum, which is very flat and sharply emarginate, and scutellar foveae very smooth, large and shallow.
</paragraph>
